'''Wendy Hughes''' (29 July 1952 <U+2013> 8 March 2014) was an [[Australia]]n actress known for her work in theatre, film and television.

==Career==
Born in [[Melbourne]], Australia<ref name=WendyHughes/> to English parents,<ref name=autogenerated5>[http://www.abc.net.au/talkingheads/txt/s1919475.htm/]</ref> Hughes was an award-winning actress.<ref>{{cite web|title=Blissfully At Ease Standing Alone|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/blissfully-at-ease-standing-alone/story-e6frg8n6-1225850050758|author=Lyndall Crisp in The Australian|date=6 April 2010}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite web|title=Focus on Wendy Hughes|url=http://www.acmi.net.au/media_wendy_hughes.htm|author=Australian Center for the Moving Image}}</ref> Her career spanned more than forty years and established her reputation as one of Australia's most prolific and finest actors.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wendy's House|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/arts/hughes-on-first/2006/05/26/1148524867137.html|year=2006}}</ref>  Hughes originally studied to become a ballerina<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|title=Wendy Hughes Biography|url=http://au.movies.yahoo.com/actor-crew/158233/wendy-hughes/bio/|author=The Movies Hype}}</ref>  but during her teenage year she turned her focus to acting and later graduated from the [[National Institute of Dramatic Art]] (NIDA)<ref name=WendyHughes/> and, after honing her skills with the [[Melbourne Theatre Company]], had her first film role in ''[[Petersen (film)|Petersen]]'' (1974).<ref name=autogenerated1 /> During the early 1970s she also had her first television parts, including appearing in ''[[Power Without Glory]]'', a television series first broadcast in 1976.<ref name=autogenerated5/>

Called "one of the important players in the development and productivity of Australian film",<ref name=autogenerated3/> Hughes worked closely with prominent Australian artists such as the  cinematographer John Seale and the writers [[David Williamson]] and [[Bob Ellis]].<ref name=autogenerated3 /> She was one of the leading players in the 1970s' "New Australian Film" renaissance.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wendy Hughes Biography|url=http://movies.msn.com/celebrities/celebrity-biography/wendy-hughes|author=MSN Entertainment}}</ref>

Hughes' first internationally known role was the character Patricia in ''[[Lonely Hearts (1982 film)|Lonely Hearts]]'' (1982).<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|title=A Celebration of Wendy Hughes|url=http://www.acmi.net.au/wendy_hughes_essay.htm|author=Philip Tyndall in Australian Center for the Moving Image}}</ref>  This role commenced a decades-long collaboration with the Dutch-Australian director [[Paul Cox]].<ref name=autogenerated2 />

As one of the leading actresses in Australian cinema, Hughes' roles in the 1970s and 1980s included those in ''[[Newsfront]]'', ''[[Kostas (film)|Kostas]]'', ''[[My Brilliant Career (film)|My Brilliant Career]]'', ''[[Lucinda Brayford]]'', ''[[Touch and Go (1980 film)|Touch and Go]]'', ''[[Hoodwink (1981 film)|Hoodwink]]'', ''[[Lonely Hearts (1982 film)|Lonely Hearts]]'', ''[[Careful, He Might Hear You]]'', ''[[My First Wife]]'', ''[[I Can't Get Started]]'', ''[[An Indecent Obsession]]'', ''[[Echoes of Paradise]]'', ''[[Boundaries of the Heart]]'', ''[[Warm Nights on a Slow Moving Train]]'' (1988) and ''[[Luigi's Ladies]]''.<ref name=autogenerated4>{{cite web|title=Wendy Hughes Filmography by Year Imdb|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0400998/filmoyear}}</ref>

Hughes made her American debut in 1987 in [[John G. Avildsen]]'s film ''[[Happy New Year (1987 film)|Happy New Year]]'' opposite [[Peter Falk]] and [[Charles Durning]]. In 1989 she starred opposite Pierce Brosnan in ''The Heist'', a TV movie made by HBO.<ref name=autogenerated4/> She continued to make occasional appearances on television, such as playing Jilly Stewart in the mini-series ''[[Return to Eden]]'' in 1983.  During the early 1990s, she spent time in the [[United States]], where she played medical examiner Dr Carol Blythe in the television series ''[[Homicide: Life on the Street]]''. She also appeared in the miniseries ''[[Amerika (TV miniseries)|Amerika]]'' and made a guest appearance as [[Lessons (Star Trek: The Next Generation)|Lieutenant Commander Nella Daren]] on ''[[Star Trek: The Next Generation]]'' as one of [[Jean-Luc Picard|Captain Picard]]'s few love interests on the show. Back in Australia, Hughes played lead roles on television in ''[[The Man from Snowy River (TV series)|The Man From Snowy River]]'' ("Snowy River: The McGregor Saga") and ''[[State Coroner (TV series)|State Coroner]]''. Film appearances around this time include ''[[Princess Caraboo (film)|Princess Caraboo]]'' and ''[[Paradise Road (1997 film)|Paradise Road]]''. 

Later film roles include ''[[Salvation (film)|Salvation]]'' (2007), ''[[The Caterpillar Wish]]'' (2006) and ''[[The Man Who Sued God]]'' (2001).<ref>{{cite web|title=Movies with Wendy Hughes|url=http://au.movies.yahoo.com/actor-crew/158233/wendy-hughes/movies/|author=The Movies Hype}}</ref> Stage appearances included Mrs Robinson in the Melbourne version of ''[[The Graduate]]'' (2001), Martha in ''[[Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?]]'' (2007)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.australianstage.com.au/reviews/melbourne/whos-afraid-of-virginia-woolf--mtc-627.html|title=Whos Afraid of Virginia Woolf? / Melbourne Theatre Company|first=Lola|last=MacMillan|work=Australian Stage|accessdate=28 May 2013}}</ref> Honor in ''[[Honour (play)|Honour]]'' (2010)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.australianstage.com.au/index.php?option=com_jevents&task=icalrepeat.detail&evid=107954&Itemid=90&year=2010&month=04&day=22&title=honour--joanna-murray-smith&uid=1293099878evt6960+1293099878recur&catids=178|title=Honour|work=Australian Stage|accessdate=28 May 2013}}</ref> and Henry Higgins' mother in ''Pygmalion'' (2012).

==Awards==
She was nominated for [[Australian Film Institute]] acting awards six times, and won the Best Lead actress award in 1983 for her performance in ''[[Careful, He Might Hear You]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aacta.org/winners-nominees/1980-1989/1983.aspx|title=AACTA <U+2013> Past Winners <U+2013> 1980<U+2013>1989 <U+2013> 1983|publisher=Australian Academy of Cinema and Television Arts (AACTA)|accessdate=8 March 2014}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Hughes had two children, a son with restaurateur Patrick Juillet and a daughter with actor [[Chris Haywood]]. She was also married to actor [[Sean Scully (actor)|Sean Scully]] for some time.<ref name=WendyHughes>{{cite web |url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/australian-actor-wendy-hughes-has-died-at-the-age-of-61/story-fnii5s3y-1226848998648 |title=Australian actor Wendy Hughes has died at the age of 61  |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=8 March 2014 |website=Herald Sun |publisher=News Ltd |accessdate=8 March 2014}}</ref><ref name=AgeReport/>

==Death==
Hughes died of cancer in the morning of 8 March 2014, aged 61. Her last TV appearance was in ''[[Miss Fisher's Murder Mysteries]]''. Actor [[Bryan Brown]] announced her death to an audience attending the play ''Travelling North'' in Sydney that afternoon, asking the audience to join him in a standing ovation in tribute to the late actress.<ref name=AgeReport>{{cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/actress-wendy-hughes-dead-at-61-20140308-34dy5.html|title=Actress Wendy Hughes dead at 61|last1=Dumas|first1=Daisy|date=8 March 2014|website=The Age|publisher=Fairfax Media|accessdate=8 March 2014}}</ref>

